# Project Overview

This project documents a threat hunt investigation involving a Windows virtual machine that was accidentally exposed to the public internet.

The purpose of the hunt was to determine whether the exposed device received brute force login attempts and whether any of those attempts resulted in successful unauthorized access.

This investigation used Microsoft Defender for Endpoint telemetry and KQL queries to review:

- Internet facing device status
- Failed login attempts
- Successful login attempts
- Suspicious remote IP addresses
- Brute force behavior
- Possible unauthorized access
- MITRE ATT&CK technique mapping
- Remediation and improvement steps

---

# Scenario Summary

During routine maintenance, the security team was tasked with investigating virtual machines in a shared services environment that may have been accidentally exposed to the public internet.

The main concern was that exposed systems could be discovered by attackers, scanners, or bots and then targeted with brute force login attempts.

Older systems were considered higher risk because they may not have had account lockout policies configured, meaning attackers could attempt repeated password guesses without being blocked.

