# Final Conclusion

This threat hunt confirmed that `windows-target-` was accidentally exposed to the public internet and received repeated failed login attempts from external remote IP addresses.

The activity was consistent with brute force or password spraying behavior. However, the investigation did not confirm successful unauthorized access.

The top suspicious remote IP addresses responsible for failed login attempts did not successfully authenticate. The successful logons that were reviewed were tied to the `labuser0` account and were not confirmed as malicious.

The most important remediation steps were to harden NSG rules, restrict RDP access to approved endpoints, implement account lockout, and enable MFA.

This project demonstrates the importance of continuously monitoring internet facing systems, reviewing failed and successful authentication activity together, and reducing public exposure before attackers can take advantage of misconfigured systems.
